The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business
 Wednesday, February 11, 2004 				 Ispat under fraud scanner
 OUR CORRESPONDENT 																								New Delhi, Feb. 10: Steel giant Ispat Industries is being placed under the scanner of the Serious Frauds Investigation Office (SFIO). The investigation has been ordered under section 235 of the Companies Act, which deals with probes into a companys affairs. 																								SFIO director . P. Arya told The Telegraph, The case of Ispat Industries has been referred to this office, but we are yet to get the legal notification.																								While stating that the referral had been made under Section 235 of the Companies Act, Arya said he had yet to get the file and did not know about the specifics of the case.																								Sources said the probe has been ordered against the steel giant for alleged exposure to Rs 8,500 crore of public funds, erosion of net worth and high accumulated losses. The case has been referred to SFIO by the department of company affairs.																								SFIO was set up to look into large-scale fraud and misappropriation of funds by companies. It takes up only those cases which DCA refers to it, after an approval by the finance minister. SFIO was specifically created for speedy and thorough investigation of serious cases. The department ordered the probe about a week ago. Ispat is the fifth case to be referred to the frauds office. 																								Daewoo Motors, DSQ Software, Design Auto and Benonza Biotech are the other cases that are being investigated by SFIO, Arya said.																								Sources said the main reason for Ispat Industries to be referred to SFIO was the erosion of almost its entire net worth. 																								Mudra Ispat and Ispat Finance held about 4 per cent stake in the company as on December 31, whereas foreign promoters held another 47.72 per cent. The public held about 15 per cent. 
